Internal WH Investigation Finds Biden’s Science Advisor 'Bullied and Demeaned Subordinates'

The two-month White House review, initiated by complaints, found Eric Lander mistreated his subordinates and violated President Biden’s workplace policies. (Politico)

Lander has apologized to staff for his “demeaning conduct” and the WH plans to keep Lander in his position after he receives counselling. (AP)

What happened to Biden’s policy warning anyone who disrespected their colleagues would be fired, “on the spot, no ifs, ands or buts”…?

Biden’s Top WH Medical Adviser QUITS After Staff Mistreatment Evidence

Eric Lander has resigned just hours after the White House confirmed an investigation had found credible evidence of him bullying staff - despite the review being completed weeks ago.

Joe Biden had insisted in his Inauguration Day address that he would fire anyone who showed disrespect to others “on the spot”, but Monday the WH signaled he’d been allowed to remain in his job.

Press Sec Jen Psaki claimed that “the president has been crystal clear with all of us about his high expectations of how he and his staff should be creating a respectful work environment.”

Lander claimed to be “devastated” to have caused hurt - or perhaps that he’d been caught?

webpage.description: President Biden's now-disgraced outgoing top science adviser Eric Lander held stocks in BioNTech as we was peddling the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine in his official role.
webpage.title: REVEALED: Biden science advisor Eric Lander, who resigned for bullying staff, had between $500,000 to $1million in BioNTech stock when he was in the White House promoting vaccines

_source.message:
Oh FFS; because of course he did. 🤡🤦🏻‍♀️

President Biden's now-disgraced outgoing top science adviser Eric Lander held stocks in BioNTech as we was peddling the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine in his official role, financial disclosure documents show.  

Upon taking his role as head of the Office of Science and Technology Policy on May 28, Lander sold off much of his stock in other pharmaceutical companies in June but held on to some of his stock in BioNTech SE, the German biotechnology company and Pfeizer’s Covid-19 vaccine partner. 

Lander did not sell $500,000 to $1 million worth of the stock until August 5, well after he'd begun publicly encouraging Americans to get vaccinated against Covid-19. The sale occurred 69 days after his confirmation, though legally Lander had until 90 days into the new job to dump the shares. 

Sauce
